30    /**
31    * General file name and file path manipulation utilities.
32    * <p>
33    * When dealing with file names you can hit problems when moving from a Windows
34    * based development machine to a Unix based production machine.
35    * This class aims to help avoid those problems.
36    * <p>
37    * <b>NOTE</b>: You may be able to avoid using this class entirely simply by
38    * using JDK {@link java.io.File File} objects and the two argument constructor
39    * {@link java.io.File#File(java.io.File, java.lang.String) File(File,String)}.
40    * <p>
41    * Most methods on this class are designed to work the same on both Unix and Windows.
42    * Those that don't include 'System', 'Unix' or 'Windows' in their name.
43    * <p>
44    * Most methods recognize both separators (forward and back), and both
45    * sets of prefixes. See the Javadoc of each method for details.
46    * <p>
47    * This class defines six components within a file name
48    * (example C:\dev\project\file.txt):
49    * <ul>
50    * <li>the prefix - C:\</li>
51    * <li>the path - dev\project\</li>
52    * <li>the full path - C:\dev\project\</li>
53    * <li>the name - file.txt</li>
54    * <li>the base name - file</li>
55    * <li>the extension - txt</li>
56    * </ul>
57    * Note that this class works best if directory file names end with a separator.
58    * If you omit the last separator, it is impossible to determine if the file name
59    * corresponds to a file or a directory. As a result, we have chosen to say
60    * it corresponds to a file.
61    * <p>
62    * This class only supports Unix and Windows style names.
63    * Prefixes are matched as follows:
64    * <pre>
65    * Windows:
66    * a\b\c.txt --&gt; "" --&gt; relative
67    * \a\b\c.txt --&gt; "\" --&gt; current drive absolute
68    * C:a\b\c.txt --&gt; "C:" --&gt; drive relative
69    * C:\a\b\c.txt --&gt; "C:\" --&gt; absolute
70    * \\server\a\b\c.txt --&gt; "\\server\" --&gt; UNC
71    *
72    * Unix:
73    * a/b/c.txt --&gt; "" --&gt; relative
74    * /a/b/c.txt --&gt; "/" --&gt; absolute
75    * ~/a/b/c.txt --&gt; "~/" --&gt; current user
76    * ~ --&gt; "~/" --&gt; current user (slash added)
77    * ~user/a/b/c.txt --&gt; "~user/" --&gt; named user
78    * ~user --&gt; "~user/" --&gt; named user (slash added)
79    * </pre>
80    * Both prefix styles are matched always, irrespective of the machine that you are
81    * currently running on.
82    * <p>
83    * Origin of code: Excalibur, Alexandria, Tomcat, Commons-Utils.
84    *
85    * @since 1.1
86    */
